{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619987"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16599"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16599"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.89,0.05,0.03,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9290"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5320"},{"type":"tags","id":"10145"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22018"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHormone replacement therapy (HRT) is prescribed to manage symptoms of menopause. The choice between oestrogen-only or combined oestrogen-progestogen therapy depends on whether a woman has had a hysterectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes why progestogen is added to oestrogen therapy in women with an intact uterus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents endometrial hyperplasia","Improves cardiovascular protection","Enhances bone mineral density","Reduces vasomotor symptoms","Decreases breast cancer risk"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe addition of progestogen \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevents endometrial hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E, which is essential in women with an intact uterus who are taking oestrogen therapy. Unopposed oestrogen stimulates endometrial proliferation, which can lead to hyperplasia and increase the risk of endometrial cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are explained below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproves cardiovascular protection\u003C/strong\u003E - progestogen does not enhance cardiovascular protection and may actually have adverse effects on lipid profiles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances bone mineral density\u003C/strong\u003E - while both hormones have some effect on bone, progestogen is not added primarily for this purpose\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces vasomotor symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E - oestrogen alone is effective for managing vasomotor symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases breast cancer risk\u003C/strong\u003E - combined therapy actually slightly increases breast cancer risk compared to oestrogen alone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen who have had a hysterectomy can safely use oestrogen-only therapy as they no longer have endometrial tissue that could become hyperplastic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Oestrogen therapy alone increases the risk of endometrial hyperplasia and cancer in women with an intact uterus.","Combined oestrogen and progestogen therapy prevents endometrial hyperplasia by opposing oestrogen\u0027s proliferative effects.","Women who have had a hysterectomy can safely use oestrogen-only hormone replacement therapy."],"references":["Menopausal hormonal therapy. Royal Australian College of General Practitioners (RACGP). Updated March 2024. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/osteoporosis/pharmacologic-approaches-to-prevention/menopausal-hormonal-therapy","A practitioner\u0027s toolkit for managing menopause. Monash University. Available from: https://www.monash.edu/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/3476072/a-practitioners-toolkit-for-managing-menopause.pdf","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16599"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T20:30:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T20:33:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9290"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75985"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"